  <section class="task-section" id="task4">
    <div class="task-header">
      <div class="task-number">04</div>
      <div class="task-title-block">
        <h2 class="task-title">Consolidating Outlook Contacts</h2>
        <div class="task-subtitle">Multiple Lists, 1,000+ Contacts Each — No Duplicates</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">

      <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        <div class="callout-label">Approach</div>
        <p>I would use PowerShell as a control tool, not as the consolidation tool itself. Its role is to scan the exported Outlook contacts, normalize the data, identify likely duplicates, and produce a review report. This gives me a reliable way to locate duplicate risk across a large contact list without touching the original Outlook data. The actual consolidation would happen in Excel, where I can manually validate each flagged group, preserve all useful contact details, and produce one clean master CSV for import back into Outlook.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="step-block">
        <div class="step-label">Tool Stack</div>
        <div class="step-text"><strong>Outlook</strong> (export) → <strong>Raw CSV Backup</strong> → <strong>PowerShell</strong> (duplicate detection) → <strong>Duplicate_Report.csv</strong> (reference only) → <strong>Excel Working File</strong> (full dataset) → <strong>Controlled Merge</strong> → <strong>Contacts_CLEAN.csv</strong> → <strong>Outlook</strong> (import)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="rule"></div>

      <p><strong style="font-weight:500; color:var(--burgundy);">Process Flow</strong></p>

      <div class="steps-list" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Outlook Export</strong>
            <p>Export the full contacts list from Outlook via File → Open &amp; Export → Import/Export → Export to a file → Comma Separated Values. This is the raw source, untouched.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Raw CSV Backup</strong>
            <p>Save a locked copy of the original export before any processing begins. This is the fallback if anything goes wrong downstream.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>PowerShell Duplicate Detection</strong>
            <p>Run a PowerShell script to normalize name and email fields, flag likely duplicates based on matching criteria, and output a structured report. No records are modified at this stage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Duplicate_Report.csv — Reference Only</strong>
            <p>Review the flagged groups. This file is for review only, no edits are made here. Each flagged group is assessed to confirm whether it's a true duplicate or a legitimate separate contact.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">5</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Excel Working File — Full Dataset</strong>
            <p>Open the full export in Excel. Use the Duplicate Report as a reference to manually validate each flagged group, preserve all useful contact details, and consolidate confirmed duplicates into single clean records.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">6</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Controlled Merge</strong>
            <p>Each confirmed contact is reviewed for completeness, including name, company, title, phone, mobile, email, notes, and category where available. Contacts without a verified email or phone are flagged for follow-up before inclusion.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">7</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Contacts_CLEAN.csv</strong>
            <p>Export the finalized dataset as a clean CSV, formatted and mapped to Outlook's import field schema. This is the only file that touches Outlook on re-import.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-item">
          <div class="step-num">8</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Outlook Import</strong>
            <p>Import via File → Open &amp; Export → Import/Export → Import from another program or file → Comma Separated Values → map fields → Import. Contacts populate in the default Contacts folder under their assigned category.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        <div style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
          <div class="day-pill" style="display:inline-block; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Note</div>
          <div class="day-title-text">On Outlook Duplicate Behavior</div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.75; color:#000000;">New Outlook may automatically hide exact or subset duplicates, but this process does not rely on hidden duplicate behavior. The full export is reviewed and consolidated before re-import.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="rule"></div>

      <p><strong style="font-weight:500; color:var(--burgundy);">Experience</strong></p>

